text:
Parliament adopted a bill to prevent the laundering of proceeds from crime

01 Nov 2019, 14:18


The Verkhovna Rada adopted Bill No. 2179 on preventing and combating the legalization (laundering) of proceeds from crime, the financing of terrorism and the financing of the proliferation of weapons of mass destruction.

Broadcast live by ZIK.
For the corresponding decision 278 people's deputies voted.
As noted in the explanatory note, the draft Law proposes to comprehensively improve national legislation in the field of financial monitoring, in particular regarding:

the introduction of generally accepted terminology in the field of preventing and counteracting the legalization (laundering) of proceeds from crime, the financing of terrorism and the financing of the proliferation of weapons of mass destruction and its essence in the international;
the application of a risk-based approach by the subjects of primary financial monitoring (SPFM) when conducting a due diligence of their clients and, accordingly, switching to case reports on suspicious transactions (activities) of their clients;
increasing the threshold amount and reducing the number of signs for mandatory reporting on financial transactions, about which SPFMs (banks, insurers, credit unions, pawnshops, exchanges, payment organizations and other financial institutions) were required to notify the State Financial Monitoring, namely, the obligation to report financial transactions to the amount of more than 400 thousand UAH (now 150 thousand UAH) and related to cash, transfer of funds abroad, by politically significant persons and clients from states that do not comply with the recommendations of international, intergovernmental organizations operating in the anti-legalization sphere;
expanding the circle of SPFMs that will report to the State Financial Monitoring about suspicious financial transactions by persons who provide information and consulting services on tax issues;
improvement of the procedure for disclosing by business entities their ultimate beneficial owners (controllers) and toughening the requirements for identifying SPFM of the beneficial owners of their customers;
introduction of international assets freezing tools and regulation of SPFM activities with assets related to terrorism and its financing;
improvement of legislative aspects that affect the quality of the investigation of crimes related to the legalization (laundering) of proceeds from crime;
improvement of legislative provisions ensuring the confidentiality of the receipt and implementation by SPFM of requests, decisions and instructions of the State Financial Monitoring, and, as a result, protection of SPFM from threats, discriminatory actions and other negative consequences associated with the implementation of measures for initial financial monitoring;
transition to tracking money transfers as a tool to prevent, detect and investigate cases of money laundering and terrorist financing, as well as to implement restrictive measures.

The draft law introduces an obligation for payment systems:

to accompany money transfers with information about the payers and the recipient of the transfer;
ensure the availability and completeness of information about the payer and payee;
establish preventive measures aimed at countering the manipulation of money received from crimes related to the legalization (laundering) of proceeds from crime, the financing of terrorism.

The online broadcast of the morning parliamentary session is available here.


